    slug: "green-muslim-the-true-custodians-of-the-earth",
    description: `Environmental degradation is one of the defining challenges of the twenty-first century — climate change, deforestation, water pollution, and waste accumulation threaten the very systems that sustain human life on this planet. While many Muslims assume that environmentalism is a Western secular concern foreign to Islamic teaching, the reality is that Islam established environmental stewardship as a religious obligation over fourteen centuries ago. Green Muslim: The True Custodians of the Earth, priced at Rs.445, is a groundbreaking book that articulates the Islamic environmental ethic with scholarly depth and practical clarity, demonstrating that being a good Muslim inherently means being an environmental steward.

The book establishes its foundation through a thorough examination of the Quranic concept of khilafah (stewardship) — the idea that human beings are appointed by Allah as custodians of the earth, not its owners or exploiters. The Quranic verses that describe the earth as a trust (amanah) entrusted to humanity, the hadith that prohibit wasteful water usage even during ablution at a flowing river, the injunctions against harming animals, cutting trees unnecessarily, and polluting shared resources are presented with their full Arabic text and scholarly commentary. These primary sources establish an Islamic environmental framework that predates the modern environmental movement by over a millennium.

Beyond the theological foundation, the book provides practical guidance for implementing Islamic environmental values in daily life. Chapters cover topics such as reducing food waste (an issue the Prophet ﷺ addressed directly when he warned against throwing away food that could still be consumed), conserving water during ablution and bathing, choosing sustainable and ethical consumer products, reducing carbon footprint through mindful transportation choices, supporting fair trade and locally sourced goods, and teaching children environmental responsibility as part of their Islamic education. The book also addresses the Islamic perspective on animal welfare, including the detailed requirements for humane treatment and slaughter that many Muslims are unaware of. At its affordable price point, Green Muslim makes an excellent addition to mosque libraries, Islamic school curricula, and home collections — providing readers with both the knowledge and the motivation to live as the true custodians of the earth that Islam calls them to be.`,
