    slug: "gunahon-ko-dho-dalny-waly-amal",
    description: `Every Muslim who has sinned — which is to say, every Muslim — carries within their heart a question of immense practical importance: is there a way to erase the record of my past mistakes and start fresh before Allah? Islam's answer is emphatically yes — through specific actions and attitudes that the Quran and Sunnah identify as expiators of sin (mughirat al-dhunub). Gunahon ko Dho Dalny Waly Amal (Acts That Erase Sins) is a focused Urdu reference priced at just Rs.200 that compiles these purifying actions into a single, accessible guide, offering hope and a clear path forward for anyone burdened by the weight of their past transgressions.

The book draws exclusively from authentic hadith that enumerate specific actions which the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) described as erasing sins. These include the well-known expiators such as performing wudu (ablution) properly — the Prophet (ﷺ) said that the five daily prayers and Friday prayers are expiation for sins committed between them, and that each wudu itself washes away minor sins. The book covers the expiation achieved through fasting — particularly the fasts of Ramadan, the six fasts of Shawwal, the fast of Arafah, and voluntary fasting on Mondays and Thursdays. The chapter on Hajj and Umrah explains the Prophet's (ﷺ) promise that an accepted pilgrimage has no reward except Paradise. Other expiators covered include charity, seeking forgiveness (istighfar), nighttime prayers (tahajjud), reciting the Quran, honoring parents, maintaining family ties, and enjoining good and forbidding evil.

Crucially, the book distinguishes between minor sins (which are erased by these good deeds) and major sins (which require specific repentance). It provides a clear framework for sincere repentance (tawbah) that includes immediate cessation of the sin, genuine remorse, firm intention never to return to it, and if the sin involved another person's rights, restoring those rights. The book also warns against despair — citing the Quranic verse in which Allah says His mercy encompasses all things, and the hadith in which the Prophet (ﷺ) said that even a person who has committed every major sin can be forgiven if they turn to Allah sincerely. For Muslims who feel overwhelmed by their past mistakes, for those who recently returned to Islamic practice after a period of neglect, and for anyone who wants to understand the Islamic path to spiritual purification, this concise and affordable booklet provides essential knowledge delivered with compassion and scholarly reliability.`,
