    slug: "hadith-ka-imam-imam-ahmad-bin-hanbal",
    description: `Imam Ahmad ibn Hanbal (164–241 AH / 780–855 CE) is one of the most towering figures in Islamic history — not only as the founder of the Hanbali school of jurisprudence but more fundamentally as one of the greatest hadith scholars the Muslim world has ever produced. Hadith ka Imam: Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal is a compact Urdu biography priced at Rs.200 that introduces readers to the life, scholarship, and extraordinary character of a man whose dedication to preserving the authentic teachings of Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) earned him the title "Imam of the Ahl al-Sunnah."

The book traces Imam Ahmad's life from his birth in Baghdad — the intellectual capital of the Abbasid Caliphate — through his decades of tireless scholarship. Readers learn about his remarkable methodology for collecting hadith: he traveled across the Muslim world, from Iraq to the Hijaz to Yemen to Syria, seeking out every living narrator of Prophetic traditions and memorizing their chains of transmission. His personal collection, the Musnad Ahmad, contains over thirty thousand hadith and remains one of the six canonical hadith collections recognized by Sunni Islam. The book explains the unique features of the Musnad — its organization by narrator rather than by topic — and its significance in hadith scholarship.

The most dramatic sections of the book cover the Mihnah (Inquisition) — the period when the Abbasid Caliph Al-Ma'mun attempted to force scholars to accept the Mu'tazili doctrine that the Quran was created rather than eternal. While many prominent scholars capitulated under threat of imprisonment and torture, Imam Ahmad refused to compromise his belief — enduring two years of imprisonment and severe beatings that left him permanently scarred. His steadfastness during the Mihnah became a defining moment in Islamic intellectual history, establishing the principle that no temporal authority has the right to dictate matters of religious belief. The book describes how his resistance ultimately prevailed, and how the position he defended became the orthodox position of Sunni Islam for all subsequent generations. For students of Islamic history, for readers seeking inspiration from the lives of great scholars, and for anyone who wants to understand the origins of Islamic hadith scholarship, this concise biography provides an accessible and inspiring introduction to one of Islam's most courageous and accomplished intellectual giants.`,
